[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:junit/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:junit/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:junit/junit] JUnit is linked as a JAR at compile-time.
[src:junit/junit] The latest version of the framework, JUnit 6, resides under package `org.junit.jupiter`.
[src:junit/junit] Previous versions JUnit 4 and JUnit 3 were under packages `org.junit` and `junit.framework`, respectively.
[src:junit/junit] A research survey performed in 2013 across 10,000 Java projects hosted on GitHub found that JUnit (in a tie with slf4j-api) was the most commonly included external library.
[src:junit/junit] Each library was used by 30.7% of projects.
[src:junit/junit] Every JUnit test class usually has several test cases.
[src:junit/junit] These test cases are subject to the test life cycle.
[src:junit/junit] Test execution - This phase is responsible for running the test and verifying the result.
[src:junit/junit] The test result will indicate if the test result is a success or a failure.
[src:junit/junit] Clean up phase - After all posttest executions are performed, the system may need to perform cleanup.
[src:junit/junit] Similar to class-level setup, there is a corresponding class-level clean up.
[src:junit/junit] The `@AfterAll` annotation is used to support class-level clean up.
[src:junit/junit] The `@AfterEach` annotation allows for cleanup after test execution.
[src:junit/junit] JUnit 6 integrates a number of tools, such as build tools, integrated development environments (IDE), continuous integration (CI) tools and many more.
[src:junit/junit] JUnit supports Apache Ant, Apache Maven and Gradle build tools, which are the most widely used project build tools.
[src:junit/junit] Build tools are vital for automating the process of building the project.
[src:junit/junit] Apache Ant, also known as Ant, is one of the build tools with the highest degree of versatility, and has the longest history out of the three build tools listed above.
[src:junit/junit] Ant centers around the `build.xml` file, used for configuring the tasks necessary to run a project.
[src:junit/junit] Ant also has an extension called Apache Ivy, which helps deal with dependency resolution.
[src:junit/junit] The project dependencies can be declared in the `ivy.xml` file.
[src:junit/junit] Ant can integrate with JUnit 5 and later by configuring the Java code coverage tools (JaCoCo), for the `ivy.xml` file.
[src:junit/junit] The `ivy.xml` can then be configured with the `java-platform-console` and `junit-platform-runner` dependencies to integrate with JUnit 5 and later.
[src:junit/junit] In contrast to Ant, Apache Maven, also known as Maven, uses a standardized and unified approach to the build process.
[src:junit/junit] Maven follows the paradigm of "convention over configuration" for managing its dependencies.
[src:junit/junit] The Java source code (or "src") can be found under the `src/main/java` directory, and the test files can be found under the `src/test/java` directory.
[src:junit/junit] It uses the Project Object Model (POM), which is an XML-based approach to configuring the build steps for the project.
[src:junit/junit] The minimal Maven with the `pom.xml` build file must contain a list of dependencies and a unique project identifier.
[src:junit/junit] Maven must be available on the build path to work.
[src:junit/junit] Maven can integrate with JUnit 5 and later using the `jacoco-maven-plugin` plugin which supports out-of-box functionality for JUnit tests.
[src:junit/junit] Different Maven goals can be specified to achieve these tasks.
[src:junit/junit] Gradle is a build tool that borrows many concepts from its predecessors, Ant and Maven.
[src:junit/junit] It uses the `build.gradle` file to declare the steps required for the project build.
[src:junit/junit] Unlike Ant and Maven, which are XML-based, Gradle requires the use of Apache Groovy, which is a Java-based programming language.
[src:junit/junit] Unlike Ant and Maven, Gradle does not require the use of XML.
[src:junit/junit] Gradle still adheres to Maven's "convention over configuration" approach, and follows the same structure for `src/main/java` and `src/test/java` directories.
[src:junit/junit] Gradle can integrate with JUnit 5 and later by configuring a plugin `jacoco` alongside the junit-platform plug-in given by the JUnit team in the build file.
[src:junit/junit] JUnit follows the paradigm of preferring extension points over features.
[src:junit/junit] The JUnit team decided not to put all features within the JUnit core, and instead decided to give an extensible way for developers to address their concerns.
[src:junit/junit] In JUnit 4, there are two extension mechanisms: the Runner API and Rule API.
[src:junit/junit] There were some disadvantages to both the Runner API and the Rule API.
[src:junit/junit] A major limitation of the Runner API is that developers must implement the entire test lifecycle, even if only a specific phase is required.
[src:junit/junit] This is too complicated and heavyweight for most use cases.
[src:junit/junit] Another major limitation is that only one runner class can be used per test case, which makes runners non-composable.
[src:junit/junit] For example, Mockito and Parameterized runners cannot be used together within the same test class.
[src:junit/junit] A major limitation of the Rule API is that it cannot control the entire test lifecycle and is therefore unsuitable for certain use cases.
[src:junit/junit] Rules are only suitable for operations that need to run before or after test execution.
[src:junit/junit] Another limitation is that class-level and method-level rules must be defined separately.
[src:junit/junit] In JUnit 5 and later, the extension API is found within the JUnit Jupiter Engine.
[src:junit/junit] The JUnit Team wants to allow the developer to hook to separate stages of a test life cycle by providing a single unified extension API.
[src:junit/junit] Upon reaching a certain life cycle phase, the Jupiter Engine will invoke all registered extensions for that phase.
[src:junit/junit] Test instance post-processing – enables developers to hook into the test instance creation phase using the `TestInstancePostProcessor` interface.
[src:junit/junit] Conditional test execution – allows tests to run only if certain conditions are met.
[src:junit/junit] Parameter resolution – allows parameters to be injected into test methods or constructors.
[src:junit/junit] Exception handling – allows developers to modify test behavior in response to exceptions instead of failing the test outright.
[src:junit/junit] Test methods must be annotated by the `@Test` annotation.
[src:junit/junit] If the situation requires it, it is also possible to define a method to execute before (or after) each (or all) of the test methods with the `@BeforeEach` (or `@AfterEach`) and `@BeforeAll` (or `@AfterAll`) annotations.
[src:junit/junit] As a side effect of its wide use, previous versions of JUnit remain popular, with JUnit 4 having over 100,000 usages by other software components on the Maven Central repository.
[src:junit/junit] In JUnit 4, the annotations for test execution callbacks were `@BeforeClass`, `@Before`, `@After`, and `@AfterClass`, as opposed to JUnit 5's `@BeforeAll`, `@BeforeEach`, `@AfterEach`, and `@AfterAll`.
[src:junit/junit] In JUnit 3, test fixtures had to inherit from `junit.framework.TestCase`.
