[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] The goal of this document is to provide comprehensive reference documentation for programmers writing tests, extension authors, and engine authors as well as build tool and IDE vendors.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] JUnit is composed of several different modules from three different sub-projects.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] The **JUnit Platform** serves as a foundation for launching testing frameworks on the JVM.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] It also defines the `TestEngine` API for developing a testing framework that runs on the platform.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] Furthermore, the platform provides a Console Launcher to launch the platform from the command line and the JUnit Platform Suite Engine for running a custom test suite using one or more test engines on the platform.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] First-class support for the JUnit Platform also exists in popular IDEs (see IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, NetBeans, and Visual Studio Code) and build tools (see Gradle, Maven, Ant, Bazel, and sbt).
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] JUnit requires Java 17 (or higher) at runtime.
[src:junit/junit5-user-guide] However, you can still test code that has been compiled with previous versions of the JDK.
